    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 33 @ 2021/2022",
    "Question": {
      "content": "What is Φ_B in the three cases in figure 1 below.",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "0, (1/√2)BA, BA",
        "(1/√2)BA, 0, BA",
        "(1/√2)BA, 0 BA",
        "2BA, (1/√2)BA, BA"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "0, (1/√2)BA, BA"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "Magnetic flux \\( \\Phi_B \\) through a surface is given by \\( \\Phi_B = B A \\cos \\theta \\), where \\( B \\) is the magnetic field, \\( A \\) is the area, and \\( \\theta \\) is the angle between \\( B \\) and the normal to the surface. In figure 1: (a) \\( \\theta = 90^\\circ \\), so \\( \\cos 90^\\circ = 0 \\), flux = 0. (b) \\( \\theta = 45^\\circ \\), so \\( \\cos 45^\\circ = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} \\), flux = \\( \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} BA \\). (c) \\( \\theta = 0^\\circ \\), so \\( \\cos 0^\\circ = 1 \\), flux = \\( BA \\). This makes 0, (1/√2)BA, BA the correct answer. The other options do not match these flux values for the given angles."
    },
    "topic": [
      "Magnetic Fields",
      "Magnetic Flux",
      "Gauss's Law",
      "Units of Measurement"
    ]
